21. These are just a FEW of 007's friends who continuously save his life. James Bond returns in No Time To Die this spring - we'll be watching for the kick-ass woman who saves the world and lets James take the credit.
20. Halle Berry was NSA agent Giacinta "Jinx" Johnson in Die Another Day. She's tough, she's smart and like every bitchin’ woman, she refuses to be tied down.
19. Nuclear physicist Dr. Christmas Jones helps Bond in The World Is Not Enough. The no-nonsense doctor played by Denise Richards assists 007 as they stop a world-destabilizing nuclear meltdown.
18. Wai Lin, played by Michelle Yeoh, is a Chinese secret agent in Tomorrow Never Dies. She and James stop a war between the US and China. Yeoh did all of her own stunts in this film.

17. Russian scientist Natalya Simonova is James' only hope to stop the GoldenEye from launching. She is able to hack the satellite and shut it down while giving James a piece of her mind. Natalya is played by Izabella Scorupco.

16. Pam Bouvier is a retired US Army pilot who helps James get his job back in License To Kill. She also helps beg the question: is Bond a super spy or a freeloader who charms smart and successful women into helping him succeed?

15. Stacey Sutton is a geologist and oil heiress fending off a hostile takeover from Zorin Industries in A View To A Kill. She saves Bond from falling to his death at the climax when she wrecks the Zorin zeppelin. Yes, we said zeppelin.

14. Kim Basinger revisits Domino Derval, now Domino Pertachi, in the not-quite-a-Bond movie Never Say Never Again. If you saw Thunderball she has kinda the same deal, but also a great ballroom dance sequence:

13. Octopussy, played by Maud Adams, is a jewel smuggler who changes her ways. She protects James when Kamal Khan tries to kill him. Bond thanks her by hooking up, then faking his death. What is it with this guy?

12. James helps Dr. Holly Goodhead save the world in Moonraker. The good doctor, played by Lois Chiles, pilots a space shuttle and handles a laser rifle. She then takes 007 "around the world" with some zero-G space sex. Doctor's orders.
11. Bond meets his match in The Spy Who Loved Me. Anya Amasova, aka Barbara Bach learns Bond killed her lover and promises to kill him, but instead falls in love. WOW James, you got lucky this time.

10. Mary Goodnight meets James in The Man With The Golden Gun. She's a junior agent played by Britt Ekland who has the hots for James until he makes her hide in a closet while he...persuades an asset. You shot the wrong shot, James!
9. Jane Seymour adds the supernatural to the Bond Girl trope in Live And Let Die. She's a mysterious tarot card reader with psychic powers so naturally her name is - *checks notes* - Solitaire.
8. In Diamonds are Forever, Bond poses as a gangster and meets smuggler Tiffany Case, played by Jill St. John. She gives up her smuggling ways for James, who thanks her by almost getting her killed.
7. Bond actually marries his next partner, Countess Tracy di Vicenzo, in On Her Majesty's Secret Service. Unfortunately, she learns the hard way why you never marry a secret agent.

6. Bond visits Japan in You Only Live Twice and works with superagent Kissy Suzuki, aka Mie Hama. Kissy helps bring down Blofeld and even fake marries James, who couldn't even be bothered to use his real name in the ceremony.
5. Domino Derval arrives in Thunderball, played by Claudine Auger. Domino saves James at the climax of the film. The lesson here: let women finish.
4. Goldfinger gave us Pussy Galore. Yes, we know. But she was also in charge of a team of female pilots called The Flying Circus and kicked Bond's ass.

3. Bond's next work wife was Tatiana Romanova in From Russia, With Love. Romanova was - get this - supposed to blackmail Bond by filming a sex tape with him but defects to MI6 after she realizes she loves him, aka "Maneuver TMZ."

2. Ursula Andress stunned audiences as Honey Ryder in Bond's first outing, Dr. No. Her swimsuit was so iconic its bikini sales skyrocketed and is now the most famous bikini ever. Bonus - Andress helped design it!
1. Lots of ladies want to kill James Bond, and for good reason. But despite his own Lothario tendencies he manages to find some world-saving women who help him come through in the clutch:
CHRISTMAS ANGEL

18) James Bond will always drive the coolest rides and almost certainly ruin them. What will he roll up next year in No Time To Die?

17) The World Is Not Enough, but the BMW Z8 sure is. James uses its stinger missiles to blow up a helicopter before ANOTHER helicopter saws it in half. At this point, Bond's insurance premiums must be through the roof.
16) Tomorrow Never Dies has our favorite car chase sequence as Bond pilots a BMW 750 iL via smartphone like a video game. Go check it out, it's a great sequence. And a great car.

15) The Aston Martin DB5 returned in Goldeneye, making a brief appearance early in the movie as James woos an MI6 analyst while simultaneously flirting with a woman trying to run him off the road. What a multitasker!

14) Much like the backbone of our shipping industry,the climax of License To Kill revolves around semi-trucks. Timothy Dalton, as Bond, tips a Kenworth W-900 B like a crooked waiter, just missing getting missiled! TRUCK YEAH.
13) Did you know James Bond was also a magician? In A View To A Kill, he takes a Renault Taxi, and with a few magic words, makes it into two taxis!

12) In the not-quite-a-Bond film Never Say Never Again, Sean Connery reprises the role but with fewer cool cars. He gets a Yamaha XJ650T bike that producers tried to make look cool. But just like Connery's toupee, it doesn't quite work.

11) Octopussy featured one of the goofiest Bond vehicles – James' partner Vijay drives a modified Baja RE, also called a Tuk Tuk. The souped up rickshaw helps them escape Kamal Khan like Road Runner fleeing The Coyote.

10) For The Spy Who Loved Me, Bond needed to get underwater to stop Karl Stromberg's evil plans. The solution – a Lotus Esprit that became a submarine. Above water, below water – find you a car that can do both.

9) In The Man With The Golden Gun, 007 now looked like Roger Moore. Here he drives an AMC Hornet that apparently makes a slide whistle noise when it does a barrel roll? Weird modification, Q, but okay.
8) Connery is back in action as Bond in Diamonds Are Forever in some American muscle - a Ford Mustang. Though he still had some trouble with American driving laws.
7) On Her Majesty's Secret Service – Bond got a facelift as George Lazenby took over the role. Tracy Di Vicenzo and her Mercury Cougar do most of the driving though and we’re here for it.
6) Sean Connery was too big for the Japanese Toyota 2000 GT used in You Only Live Twice; producers had to IRL modify the car by cutting off the roof so he could fit.
5) Because James Bond is never happy, Q added more modifications to The Aston Martin DB5 in Thunderball. Like this shield for when you need to block out the haters.

4) One of the reasons Goldfinger is a classic – Bond's modified Aston Martin DB5. It has: - Bulletproof glass - Revolving license plates - An ejector seat Unfortunately this car would not pass emissions in 2019.
3) Connery returned as Bond in From Russia With Love, driving a modified Bentley Mark IV with a car phone. A phone in a car?
2) Sean Connery debuted as James Bond in 1963's Dr. No in a topless Sunbeam Alpine Series II. No modifications, except the ability to trick villains into falling down a mountain and dying.
1) What do you think when you hear James Bond? If your answer was "epic car chases and sick whips" then this will be your favorite Twitter thread of all time.

16: Like Blane, Duckie demonstrates growth at the end of the movie. He encourages Andie to go after Blane, wishing her well. He finally shows her true friendship, while Blane gives her the romantic challenge she needs. Maybe it’s really win/win/win in the end? What do you think?
15: Still, at the end of the day, it’s Duckie who does lift Andie up and it’s Duckie who picks up her pieces and helps to put her back together when she’s feeling broken.

14: But Duckie’s devotion to Andie is also his downfall. He finds it hard to talk to her seriously about his feelings, and also gets angry at her for showing interest in other guys. He doesn’t respect her boundaries, and while they talk a lot, he doesn’t always listen.
13: He just loves Andie SO MUCH, y’all.
12: When Steff is horrible about Andie, Blane walks away, and it’s Duckie who jumps to defend her. Or, at least, to punish Steff.
11: Duckie is always there for Andie – even sometimes when she doesn’t necessarily want him there – and he’s constantly complimenting her and supporting her.

10: Andie and Duckie have been friends since they were kids, and they get each other in a way no one else really can. They have a shared background and interests, and they deeply care about one another.
9: Cutting through all this, however, is Duckie. Oh, Duckie. He has his own charm, what with his vintage fashion and his lip syncing.

8: Blane does realize his mistake and apologizes to Andie. What makes the apology more meaningful is the way he shows how he really listens to her and knows her. It’s enough for Andie to forgive him, and it seems like they're in a good place.

7: That is until it all gets too much for him. He low-key ghosts Andie as a result of pressure from his parents and douchey friend Steff. It clearly breaks his heart, but worse, it breaks hers. Ngl, even if you’re Team Blane, this is a pretty shitty moment.

6: Their disastrous first date reinforces the idea that they’re incredibly uncomfortable in each other’s worlds and their class divide immediately places a huge obstacle in their budding relationship. But Blane is sweet and charming and persistent in spite of all this.

5: Of course, he’s very rich, and Andie kind of holds that against him – but there’s no doubt that’s also part of his appeal to her. She has a lot of pride, but she also secretly yearns for the kind of cushy life her better-off classmates have.

4: There’s a certain awkward charm to Andie and Blane’s interactions that remains endearing. Blane himself doesn’t say a whole lot, but his interest in Andie radiates from every tiny gesture. He brings out her sarcastic and flirty side, and she clearly has fun with him.
3: The two of them have incredible chemistry. From the outset, it’s all longing looks culminating in a series of very hot kisses.
2: First up, our main man Blane. He’s peak ‘80s handsomeness. Those baby blue eyes, that shy smile, that semi-mullet? Andie is obviously attracted to him, and we don’t blame her.

1: It’s one of the most famous – and perhaps most controversial – love triangles of all time. In Pretty in Pink, Andie chooses Blane, the handsome rich boy, over her best friend Duckie. Did she make the right choice? Let’s take a closer look at each guy…

12. Patel’s career so far has featured diverse roles, and he brings something unique to each one – but no matter what, he’s always compulsively watchable. We can’t wait to see what he does next.

11. Finally, in Hotel Mumbai, Patel plays heroic young waiter Arjun, leading a stellar cast including Armie Hammer and Jason Isaacsi. The movie is based on the events of the 2008 terrorist attack at the Taj Mahal Palace Hotel in India. It's harrowing but remarkable.

10. The Wedding Guest takes Patel into action thriller territory. He plays a man with a secret who kidnaps a bride-to-be and takes her on the run. The role is different from anything he’s done before, and an absolute heart-stopper.

9. In a career already full of powerful performances, Lion features one of Patel’s greatest. Based on a true story, Patel stars as Saroo, an Australian man who uses Google Earth to find his biological family in India. Bonus: Patel's hair reaches peak strength here.

8. BTW, how do you feel about Dev Patel in period costume? If the answer is VERY GOOD (as it should be), then The Man Who Knew Infinity is an unmissable movie. In it, he creates a stunning portrayal of real-life mathematical pioneer Srinivasa Ramanujan.

7. Patel then teamed up with Robert Sheehan and Zoë Kravitz in The Road Within, in which they play a trio of troubled young people who go on a life-changing road trip. The chemistry between the three of them is electric, and Patel gives the role his all.

6. Proving his versatility once again, Patel returned to TV for the first time since his unforgettable role as Anwar on Skins, doing a two-season stint on The Newsroom. His time as blogger Neal cemented Patel as one to watch.

5. In The Best Exotic Marigold Hotel and its sequel The Second Best Exotic Marigold Hotel, Patel shows off his considerable comedic chops as the ambitious and well-meaning – but somewhat inept – manager of the titular hotel, Sonny.
4. Patel followed that up with something completely different: The Last Airbender. For his role as anti-hero Zuko, Patel underwent intense training in martial arts.

3. Of course, we've got to start with Slumdog Millionaire. It's the movie that launched him to international stardom, and with good reason. Romantic and moving, Patel gives the kind of performance that burrows its way into your heart and stays there for a very long time.
2. But we're here to remind you that Dev Patel has been an interesting and compelling actor for over a decade. Let's take a look at some of his career highlights to date…

10. Their relationship goes through many (many) ups and downs. It bends, but it never breaks. Sorry Klare, but Fleabag is actually the great love of Claire’s life — and vice versa.

9. Claire does everything she can to help and support Fleabag — and Fleabag quite literally drops everything to be there for Claire whenever she needs it. Contrary to our initial impression, it’s not just Claire picking up after her younger sister; they very much need each other.
8. Still, even in their darkest moments, their bond persists.
7. Though they hurt one another, the most painful thing for each of them is actually when they’re separated.
6. They might be awkward with physical affection, but they can tell each other anything – and say so much with a single look.
5. While these feelings color the way they treat each other, there remains a subtle but powerful undercurrent of love running through all their interactions.

4. Fleabag sometimes feels inadequate next to her rich, successful sister, and their relationship doesn’t seem totally equal at first. But we come to realize that Claire also gets insecure around her witty, vivacious younger sibling.

3. But this is Phoebe Waller-Bridge we’re talking about, so of course the dynamic between the sisters becomes one of the most complex, interesting, and ultimately heartwarming aspects of the whole damn series.

2. When we’re first introduced to Claire, Fleabag describes her sister as “uptight and beautiful”. The two immediately bicker and the scene seems to set up an antagonistic relationship. In the hands of a lesser writer, that's all it might have been...

Which acts are on your lineup?
Fleetwood Mac - The Dance: In 1997, Fleetwood Mac reunited to play songs from the iconic Rumours album. It's in the title: you WILL dance.
Sheryl Crow - Live at the Capitol Theatre: Name the first @SherylCrow song you can think of. She sings it in this show.
LCD Soundsystem - Shut Up and Play the Hits: If you were sad you couldn't be at their "last" show at Madison Square Garden in 2011, this one's for you. Look for the @DonaldGlover cameo.
Aretha Franklin - Divas Live: Come for a high-energy tribute to the Queen of Soul, stay for the early 2000s fashions.
Prince - Sign O' the Times: We recommend turning the lights down and the sound up for this one to fully bask in the fact that Prince could do it all.
Talking Heads - Stop Making Sense: David Byrne in a big suit. That's all you need to know. (Actually, it's not, but we won't spoil this masterpiece.)
